Agglomeritive Heirarchical Clustering: What and Why?

Agglomerative Heirarchical Clustering uses a bottom-up approach to clustering. It works from the bottom (all of the instances individually) and continuously clusters the instances based on the differences of all of those clusters. It first considers each attribute to be its own cluster, and measures the difference (difference differences depending on which method you choose) and then works it’s way up to find the larger clusters of instances. Within the dataset I chose, it is important to account for the large range and potential outliers, which is why I chose to use the average-linkage method for my hclust() command as you can see in my code. I also chose to use the scale() function which scales the data, and works with the center of the numerical vector to then recalibrate the data. This is important with heirarchical clustering because we do not want any outliers, even if we are working with small outliers here. It is best to have as balanced data as possible, and this will balance the data completely. This model and this data will paint a great picture as to which cities have similar annual rainfall

Choosing your Data

My data file is called ‘precip’ and it is one of the existing datasets in R. This data measures the average amount of precipitation (in) in 70 U.S. cities. There are 2 data files attached to this report: the first one (precip.csv) is just the rainfall, which is the previously loaded data. The next dataset (precip.NEW.csv), which is the same dataset but I manually typed in the cities that correspond with the rainfall because those do not show up in the original dataset, and also other elements are included in that data file that will be discussed as we go through this report. I added these in to make it easier for the reader of this report to follow along.

For this report, our goal is the cluster (classify) the 70 cities based on similar rainfall (in). Our attributes are numerical values linked with a name of a city. The min, max of the dataset (as I mentioned before) is [7.0in, 67.0in], which shows a range of 60in, which is why we must account for the large range by scaling the data.

Time to cluster!

Here, we will run our r code to cluster the data. The agnes() command is from the cluster package [previously loaded earlier in this report], and this will help us to cluster our data. This is essentially the same code as hclust(), but that is from the stats package in R. The agnes() function does give us one bit of information that hclust() doesn’t: our clustering coefficent. The clustering coefficient tells us how strong the clustering structure is. We want a strong clustering structure, that means we have a good cluster model!

In this code, you can see that I have a parameter of method = “average”. This means I am using the average-linkage method of clustering. The average-linkage measures the average difference between each pair in the two clusters, instead of the maximum or minimum linkage that just uses the direct calculated differences. The issue with the average-linkage method is it depends on the numerical measurements of the dataset, but this dataset has reasonable numerical values that we JUST scaled in the above code chunk, so it would still work well.

precip_clustered <- agnes(precip_scaled, metric = "euclidean", method = "average")

Creating the precipitation dendrogram

What is a dendrogram?

A dendrogram is a representation of heirarchical clustering. There are many methods for representation of data, but a dendrogram is a form of a visual tree with nodes and shows how the clusters form at each node. When reading the dendrogram, it is important to start at the bottom of our tree because this is agglomeritive heirarchical clustering, which starts at the bottom and works its way up. You can see as well on the y-axis that there are values, heights, which measure similarity of the clusters and connections. The higher the height, the less similarity two clusters have to one another.

Precip_scaled Dendrogram

First, when preparing this dendrogram, I used the hclust() function from the base R package. This is because I wanted to be able to present the clusters using the rect.hclust() function. For hclust() I needed to calculate the distances first, as I did, and named them ‘distances’. Then, using base R commands, I plotted the dendrogram.

#retrieved from https://uc-r.github.io/hc_clustering

distances <- dist(precip_scaled, method = "euclidean", diag = FALSE, upper = TRUE)
precip_scaled_dendo <- hclust(distances, method = "average", members = NULL)
precip_scaled_dendo
## 
## Call:
## hclust(d = distances, method = "average", members = NULL)
## 
## Cluster method   : average 
## Distance         : euclidean 
## Number of objects: 70
plot(precip_scaled_dendo, cex = 0.6)
rect.hclust(precip_scaled_dendo, h = 0.5, border = 2:5)

In this dendrogram, you can see how the clusters are formed at height of .5, which shows us 7 different clusters. As we cluster at different heights, our clusters change. You can see this detailed below.

I also wanted to present a different format, one tracing clusters through color as they move up a the tree to the specific height. We do this through the color_branches() command from the dendextend package. You can see this shown below.

Clustering at different heights

Now, we will analyze clustering at different heights. The height of a dendrogram shows disimilarity between clusters. The taller the branch (more height), the larger difference in distances between clusters. In our rect.hclust() command, we can choose the number of clusters based on the height of dissimilarity described above. Visually, I will represent these at each height levels of: 0.5, 1.0, 1.5, and 2.0. I have plotted the 0.5 above, and you can see the remaining noted in the next plots.

I am choosing to do this because at h = 0.5, we can see the first real measures of disimilarities in the data, with the first measures of taller branches.

Manually creating the clusters

Because agglomeritive heirarchical clustering is unsupervised, we need to create these clusters to measure the quality of the clustering. We will do this using the cutree() function, which will split our data into 7 clusters, based on where they are drawn in the dendrogram with h = 0.5.

clusters <- cutree(precip_scaled_dendo, h = .5)

Wait, but what if we predicted another city…?

As we can see, R chose the number of clusters based on the heights. So, what if we added another city? How would we cluster it based what we know about the distances/heights?

Our random city will be called Rainbow Land, and it has a precipitation value of 43.2 in. Well, we know that with a precipitation of 43.2, the instance would start in close quarters with Providence, who has a preciptation value of 42.8, meaning they are only .4in away from eachother. We can see the cluster data written above, which shows us that Rainbow Land would fall in cluster 4, as it is very close to the mean, and also within the range of preciptation for cluster 4.

Model evaluation (using a human)

Because this is unsupervised clustering, and we do not have a ‘right’ answer for our clusters in relation to precipitation, we do not have a computer algorithm that will display an accurate evaluation for us. So, because the purpose of heirarchical clustering is to cluster based on a numerical value, we will ask a human to cluster (classify) 7 cities into what they think is the correct bin (class) based on their numerical values.

The data shown below titled ‘human_prediction’ is the random sample of 7 cities chosen from our dataset. I used the code ‘sample_n(7, replace = FALSE)’ to do this, but if I submitted that code, it would take a random sample each time the code was ran, so I wrote out the 7 that were chosen.

human_prediction = precip.NEW %>%

When evaluating the human prediction, as this table output demonstrates, the human predictor was indicitive of this model not being the best. I calcualted the probability of correct by stating on the numerator how many cities the human classified just like the computer did, and the denominator was the test sample size, which is 7. I calculated the p_incorrect, as seen above, and our p_incorrect for predicting this testing set of 7 values was 71.4%. This is a huge probability of incorrect classification, further demonstrating that this model was not the best.

What other model can we use?

Well, after I saw that this model of agglomeritive heirarchical clustering was not the most predictive, I chose to preform a decision tree on the data, too, to see how this classification would classify our unknown data point of Rainbow Land with a precipitation of 43.2in.

Here, we can see the numerical representations of our decision tree, which show that the root node error for the decision tree is 64.2%. This is not a great error statistic, but we do see our CP value decreasing with each split, showing the tree increasingly gaining predictability as it goes through splits.

plot(precip_decision_tree, uniform=TRUE, margin = 0.3)
text(precip_decision_tree, use.n=TRUE, all=TRUE, cex=0.7)

#http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/add-titles-to-a-plot-in-r-software

As we can see on the tree, the data splits first at precipitation >= 38.15in, where we can see the counts for each cluster (ex. 1/5/4/25/10/4/21). On the true side of that split, we have another split at precipitation >= 49.15. This then splits those counts into either true (1/5/0/1/0/0/0) or false (0/0/0/24/1/0/0). On the false side, we have the next split at precipitation < 27.5in. For true, we have (0/0/4/0/9/4/0). For false, we have (0/0/0/0/0/0/21).

As for our city Rainbow Land, we can see it go through the tree! First, it would split to the left (true), because 43.2in>=38.15in. Then, it gets split from that node, to the right leaf, leaving Rainbow Land to be classified as class 4.

Evaluating the Decision Tree

Here, we will evaluate our decision tree.

train_control <- trainControl(method = "LOOCV") 

modelA1 <- train(as.factor(cluster_number) ~ precipitation, data = precip.NEW, 
                 method = "rpart", 
                 trControl = train_control)

print(modelA1)

We can see here that we used Leave-One-Out cross validation as our resampling method, and we can see in the code that we used rpart as our evaluation method in our model. This illustrated for us that our accuracy for the decision tree was about 78.57%, which is much higher than our agglomeritive heirarchical clustering model. This is because our original model was unsupervised, and we were predicting a classification that does not truely exist in our data. With our decision tree, although our data was still unsupervised, our clusters were already drawn out from our previous model, so our LOOCV showed us that our data actually has somethign to predict. In this case, our accuracy was quite high.

In conclusion, our heirarchical clustering model was not the greatest. Our decision tree model was much more efficient, and painted a better picture of our classification. Our human evaluation metric for our heirarchical clustering model showed us that our human predictor was much stronger, showing us the probabilty of error of our clustering model. Overall, our decision tree model was much better.
